                        <msItem xml:id="MS_Thurston_26-item1" n="1">
                            <title key="">Vaṣiyetnāme-yi Birgeli</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ota" key="">وصیت‌نامهٔ برگلی</title>
                            <incipit xml:lang="ota"> الحمد لله الذي هدانا للاسلام و جعلنا من امة
                                محمد عليه الصلوة والسلام الخ</incipit>
                            <author key="person_59888184">
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">Birgivî Mehmet Efendi, approximately 1522-1573</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">برگوی محمد افندی</persName> <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn">Taḳīüddīn Muḥammed bin Pīr ʿAlī Birgeli</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">تاقی الدین محمد بن پیر علی برگلی</persName> <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn">Meḥmed bin Pīr ʿAlī Birgevī</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">محمد بن پیر علی برگوی</persName>
                            </author>
                            <title key="work_9567">Vaṣiyet-i Muḥammed bin Pīr ʿAlī</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ota" key="work_9567">وصيت محمد بن پیر علی</title>
                            <note>NOTE: This record has been automatically generated with minimal
                                modification from the corresponding entry in a printed catalogue. It
                                may contain errors. Please, consult the References section below for
                                more information.</note>
                            <note>The well-known exposition of the Muslim faith, both in its
                                theoretical and practical aspects, according to the Sunnite creed, a
                                kind of Muslim catechism, by Taḳīüddīn Muḥammed bin Pīr ʿAlī Birgeli
                                or Bergevī (a native of Berga or Pergamum), who was born A.H. 929=
                                A.D. 1523, and died A. H. 980 or 981=A.D. 1573, 1574. It was
                                completed A.H. 970=A.D. 1562, 1563, comp. H. Khalfa iii. p. 373, No.
                                1615; G. Flügel iii. p. 127; Rieu, p. 6; W. Pertsch, p. 52, and
                                Berlin Cat., pp. 37 and 125; Cat. des MSS. et Xylographes, pp. 168
                                and 461; J. Aumer, pp. 4 and 5; Fleischer, Dresden Cat., No. 59, and
                                Cat. Lips., No. 6; Krafft, p. 163; Zenker, No. 1463 sq.; and Journal
                                Asiatique, 1843, ii. pp. 32 and 55, and 1859, i. p. 524 (in the last
                                two publications all the printed editions and translations are
                                enumerated). Chief Eastern editions since A.H. 1218 in Scutari,
                                Constantinople, and Būlāk; a metrical Tartar translation appeared in
                                Kasan, 1802. Some select portions have also been printed in
                                Dieterici's Chrestomathie Ottomane, Berlin, 1854, pp. 38-43. French
                                translation by Garcin de Tassy in his 'Exposition de la foi
                                musulmane,' Paris, 1822, and in his 'L'islamisme d'après le Coran,'
                                Paris, 1874. Beginning: الحمد لله الذي هدانا للاسلام و جعلنا من امة
                                محمد عليه الصلوة والسلام الخ. Dated A. H. 1088=A. D. 1677/1678, by
                                Velī bin ʿAbdülkerīm.</note>
